The use of morphometric analysis in amphipods has been suggested to serve as a complement of description using traditional character keys (
Riedlecker et al. 2009
). A study on
Niphargus
amphipods showed that clades defined by molecular data can be diagnosed using morphometric analysis (
Flot et al. 2010
). The overall size of species is known to be highly variable within Crangonyctidae (e.g. Zhang & Holsinger 2003 , Svavarsson & Kristjansson 2006 ,
Culver et al. 2010
) and may reflect variation in habitats. The variation in body size may reflect the phylogenetic relationships, where different lineages have occupied groundwater habitats with different pore sizes. The pore size may also have been an important selective factor on body size (
Culver et al. 2010
) and resulted in convergence in body size and lack of phylogenetic dependence.
